<BaseLayout title="Editorial Team | FreelancePricingCalc" description="Meet the editorial team behind FreelancePricingCalc — experienced independent contractors and tax professionals who ensure accuracy.">
  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p>FreelancePricingCalc is developed and maintained by professionals with direct, long-term experience as independent contractors and freelance business advisors. All content is reviewed before publication and updated when tax rates, market benchmarks, or industry standards change.</p>

  <h2>Independent Contractor Experience</h2>
  <p>Our editorial team includes members with more than ten years of full-time experience as independent contractors, building and operating multi-discipline freelance practices across content strategy, digital marketing, and creative direction. That experience spans every phase of the freelance pricing journey — starting out underpriced and overworked, learning the hard lessons about self-employment taxes and overhead costs, rebuilding a rate structure from the ground up using the kind of backward-calculation methodology that drives this site, and eventually raising rates significantly while reducing working hours. This team brings that lived experience to every page of FreelancePricingCalc — not abstract theory, but the practical calculations that determine whether a freelance business is financially sustainable — along with a deep understanding of the psychological barriers (imposter syndrome, fear of client rejection, undervaluing specialized expertise) that cause freelancers to underprice themselves. This side of the team leads all methodology and content decisions, reviews every guide and FAQ, and ensures the site reflects the realities of freelance business in today's market.</p>

  <h2>Tax Expertise</h2>
  <p>Our team also includes Enrolled Agents — federally licensed tax practitioners authorized to represent taxpayers before the IRS — with a practice focused on self-employed individuals and small business owners. This expertise covers quarterly estimated taxes, self-employment tax, qualified business income (QBI) deductions, retirement plan contributions, and home office deductions, and how profoundly most new freelancers underestimate the tax implications of self-employment. This is the foundation of the tax component of FreelancePricingCalc's calculations: this side of the team reviews all tax-related content, ensures that the self-employment tax treatment in our calculator is accurate and current, and contributes to the tax comparison guides that help freelancers understand the true cost of self-employment versus employee status.</p>

  <h2>Editorial Standards</h2>
  <p>All content on FreelancePricingCalc is reviewed against primary sources — IRS publications, BLS wage and benefits data, and published freelance industry surveys. We do not accept sponsored content from platforms, marketplaces, or service providers. Tax rates and thresholds are updated annually following IRS announcements. FreelancePricingCalc is an informational resource only. Nothing on this site constitutes legal, financial, or tax advice; consult a qualified professional for your specific situation.</p>
</BaseLayout>
